By Zhang Diyang, southern weekend reporter

Staff editor | Wu Xiaoyu

The autopsy and pathological analysis of three deceased patients with NCP have been completed.

On February 16,2020, the autopsy work of the country's first deceased patient with NCP was completed at Wuhan's Golden Pool Hospital, it was done by Liu Liang, president of the Hubei Forensic Science Association and Professor of Forensic Pathology at the Tongji Medical College, and his team. As of February 24, Liu Liang and his team had dissected the remains of nine patients with neopneumonia.

Liu Liang said his team, in collaboration with Wang Guoping, a professor of pathology at Huazhong University of Science and Technology, has completed three diagnostic tests and a detailed anatomical report will be released soon. The remaining 6 cases still need further study by IMMUNOHISTOCHEMISTRY and special staining.

On the evening of February 24, Liu Liang and Wang were interviewed online, including by southern weekend.

1
It's not just the lungs

1

###It's not just the lungs

"NCP is a new disease, and we haven't done a lot of research on its pathogenesis or its lethal mechanism. It's not clear which organ, tissue, or cell of the body the virus is attacking, " Liu Liang explained, an autopsy of a deceased patient with NCP helps to clarify these issues.

Of the nine bodies Liu Liang's team dissected, the male to female ratio was roughly the same, but they were older, mostly in their 60s and 70s, with the oldest over 80 and the youngest over 52.

So far, Liu Liang and Wang's team have completed three of these pathologic diagnoses.

Liu Liang told southern weekly that there were similarities in pathological changes between the pneumonia caused by the SARS virus and the new coronavirus, but that the new coronavirus also had its own characteristics.

Microscopically, Liu Liang found a lot of mucus in a section of the lung of a patient with neocoronary pneumonia. "The presence of the secretion suggests that clinical care should be vigilant. "

In patients with NCP, alveolar function is impaired, and if the airway is blocked by mucus again, clinical signs of Hypoxia may occur. "To improve the patient's anoxic state, the airway needs to be opened and the mucus must be diluted and dissolved, " Liu Liang said

In clinical practice, Liu Liang notes, simply giving oxygen to a patient without the mucus being dissolved can be counterproductive. "positive pressure of oxygen can push the mucus deeper and wider, exacerbating the patient's lack of oxygen. "

In addition, from the anatomical case, the pathological changes of the new coronary pneumonia not only can damage the lungs, but also may cause damage to the immune system and other organs of the body.

Autopsies of patients with NCP may also shed light on the route of transmission of the virus. Liu Liang's team performed nucleic acid tests on different organs during the autopsy. "viruses have been found in some organs and some organs have been ruled out, but the results from different cases and organs are not quite consistent, and these issues need further analysis, " he said

Some scholars have previously proposed that some new severe pneumonia patients will burst myocarditis or commonly known as "Broken Heart Syndrome" stress cardiomyopathy. Liu Liang responded that the possibility that NCP causes fulminant myocarditis needs further discussion, but that it causes "broken heart syndrome" is less likely.

In addition to Liu Liang's team, a team from Shanghai Ruijin Hospital in Wuhan is currently carrying out the autopsy of the deceased with NCP, and has already dissected two cases. "from a scientific point of view, the more anatomy, the better, " Wang said. "There are now 11 cases, and the results can tell us something. "

2
"There are few qualified autopsy rooms in the country. "

2

###"There are few qualified autopsy rooms in the country. "

Liu Liang, 59, has been working as a forensic pathologist for more than 30 years. He has performed autopsies in major cases, such as the death of Professor Cheng Shuliang from prostitution and the sudden death of Ran Jianxin from Badong County, Hubei Province, liu Liang also testified as the first expert-assisted witness in the case of "trapping the police gate" in Huangshan City.

Seventeen years ago, Liu Liang performed an autopsy on a SARS victim. He was impressed by the fact that the pathological anatomy during SARS was a little faster than it is now, and it was started more than 10 days after the death cases appeared in China.

After the new crown pneumonia outbreak, Liu Liang's team submitted a report to the Hubei provincial authorities on Jan. 24, emphasizing autopsy's necessity and feasibility. On the 29th, they received approval.

Liu Liang then contacted a number of hospitals, "all the doctors say this is good, but when it comes to specific programs, the hospital needs to ask for a report. ". In addition, hospitals lack the space to perform autopsies and are concerned about the risks involved.

Liu Liang was worried that if he did not do the autopsy in time, "there would be a delay in emergency treatment and an impact on future research. " . He then publicised the need for dissection on several occasions.

On February 15, Liu Liang was invited by the MHA to attend a meeting on issues related to autopsy of new coronary pneumonia.

At 21:00 on Feb. 15, Liu Liang received a phone call from Zhang Dingyu, the director of Jinyintan Hospital. "One is ready for autopsy. ". At 3:50 am on the morning of the 16th, Liu Liang performed the first autopsy in the negative pressure operating room of the hospital, and 14 hours later, they completed the second autopsy. Before the autopsy, Liu Liang and his team observed a moment of silence.

Dissecting the body of a patient with new crown pneumonia required higher levels of protective equipment, and Liu Liang's team also faced a lack of protective equipment in the hard pressed city of Wuhan.

After several autopsies, Liu Liang felt that patients and families had learned more about the anatomy through media campaigns, and that clinicians had told him that family members were now more receptive than before when communicating about the donation.

But the autopsy site still doesn't solve. "If the dissecting room is not up to standard, it will lead to delayed dissection and concerns about dissection, " said Liu Liang, who said negative pressure dissecting rooms were built in Beijing and Guangdong to meet Biosafety Requirements in 2003 in response to the SARS outbreak, but after a long time no similar epidemic, those autopsy room almost deserted, "as far as I know, there is almost no qualified autopsy room. ".

"there can not be another lag like today, " Liu Liang said, suggesting that regions should build up-to-standard autopsy rooms in response to the outbreak.
